Brassica rapa Pak Choi

   [3878.jpg]
    Authority   L.
      Family    Magnoliopsida:Dilleniidae:Capparales:Cruciferae
     Synonyms
   Common names Pak Choi
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 3878

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION An erect, glabrous, dull green, herbaceous plant
   reaching 15-30 cm in height in the vegetative state and up to 70 when
   flowering. Leaves about 7 x 20 cm, arranged spirally, not forming a
   compact head but spreading. USES All above-ground parts are edible, but
   the succulent petioles are often the prefered part. It is used in soups
   and stir-fried dishes. It is used for decorating dishes but is seldom
   eaten raw, neither pickled. GROWING PERIOD Biennial, cultivated as an
   annual. Harvesting may take place 21 days after planting but it usually
   takes place between 30-45 days. COMMON NAMES Pak choi, Chinese cabbage,
   Celery cabbage, Chou de Chine, Chou de Shangton, Paksoi, Pacai, Sawi
   putih, Pak choi, Kapis, Pechay, Pechhaay, Spei khiew, Kaad chiin,
   Phakkat-khaokwangtung, Hong-tae, Hong-how.
   FURTHER INF Pak choi is widely cultivated in southern and central China
   and Taiwan. Vernalization at 5-12Â°C for 10-40 days is effective
   immediately following germination. Over-vernalization induces premature
   flowering, sometimes even at the seedling stage. Yields may be 10-20
   t/ha for small cultivars and 20-30 t/ha for large cultivars.

   Sources
   Siemonsma J 1993 pp 130-134 [TEMP, LIG, DRA, TEXT, FER, PH, PHO]

